Here is a batch of my latest cabochons all polished up.  For the last couple of years I have been coming up with a process for a glass technique, inspired by Mokume Gane.  Mokume Gane is a ancient Japanese sword making technique.  One of the reasons I love the technique is because of its results represent a natural feel. Some like wood grain, others like the inside of a beautiful rock. 
This process takes a lot of time and patience.  I am happy with where this technique is taking me.  Each time I make a batch, I learn something new or have a new idea.  The technique is endless. 
These will be set in Sterling Silver and available soon. I hope you like them as much as I do.  Thanks for looking. #headyart #bestofglass #mossyglass #cabochon #glassart

Fire/Amber Purple/Illuminati 😍💎😍 these wags are looking awesome. The AP will get a lot more purple once it's been shaped and restruck. I use a pretty reducing flame when I'm stacking reversals so it tends to wash out the pretty striking colors in the linework. Once the full section has been formed it can be heated nice and hot and that will set the amber purple back ro basically clear and then you use the flame and or the kiln to bring out the purples. #themoreyouknow

Dots! ❤️ There is often confusion on what to call the implosion dot technique. I hear it called “dot stack” more often than “dot implosion”. It’s become common to hear reference to any dots as “dot stacks”, but there are a few techniques that incorporate dots. These pendants feature two techniques - dot implosion centers with dot stacked borders. I hope you guys like them :) These are coming with to @greatestshopever September 6th and 7th, thanks for looking!
